y, and there are a couple of telegram sessions from earlier that have completed.\n\nThe other sessions include the cron:53c5832a daily briefing which finished at 23:16 UTC, a few more cron and telegram sessions that have all ended, plus some additional telegram and cron entries that also show as done. There's a running cron:e7885813 process and some other subagent sessions listed as well.\n\nLooking at what's actually running right now, I can see the main cron:ed2d0b5d with its 3 child sessions, cron:6f3323ef running, the recently finished cron:53c5832a daily briefing, and cron:e7885813 which appears to have ended around 23:14 UTC.\n\nNow I'm comparing the baseline state against what's currently active to identify what changed. The cron:53c5832a process completed normally at 23:16 UTC as expected, and cron:e7885813 also ended—likely from that same 23:14 UTC instance that the baseline captured.\n\nThe other sessions that show as done in the list are all stale entries from previous hours, so they don't represent new changes. The real question is whether the cron:e7885813 instance actually terminated or if it's still running under a different instance. Looking at the heartbeat state, cron:e7885813 was recorded as running at 23:24 UTC, but checking the current sessions, it shows as done with an endedAt timestamp around 23:14 UTC—which is actually earlier than the baseline itself, so that doesn't quite line up. I'm trying to parse the session key more carefully—it looks like there are two distinct cron:e7885813 entries, one that's done and one that's still running, so I need to figure out which one is the current state. Looking at the session details, `cron:e7885813` was running in the baseline but is now showing as done, and there's a new child subagent session that spawned under `cron:ed2d0b5d`. The status check confirms these are both new changes since the baseline was recorded. Looking at the cron:ed2d0b5d session, it's been running for about 8 minutes since 23:20 UTC, with 3 child sessions spawned during that time—all of which have completed already. Comparing this to the baseline state from 23:24 UTC, these child sessions are new spawns that weren't tracked before. Looking at the baseline data, I can see that cron:ed2d0b5d was already running at 23:24 with 3 child sessions, but the session list shows only 2 specific child sessions with IDs, so I need to figure out which ones are new since the baseline was recorded.\n\nComparing the two lists, ba49ac6d and c2d275a5 are new spawns that appeared in the current state, while 8d8e1952 and 8bffa95f are older entries. The cron:e7885813 session transitioned from running in the baseline to done, which is another state change worth noting.\n\nLooking at the bigger picture, the three child sessions spawning are normal agent monitoring behavior, and the cron:e7885813 session completing is expected. So really, no new failures or blockers have emerged—the pipeline is still healthy, and the Telegram delivery issue from 22:47 remains the only unresolved problem."},{"type":"text","text":"Comparing current state (23:29 UTC) vs. baseline (23:24 UTC):\n\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d` still running ✅ (3 child sessions: 2 new subagents spawned, 1 from baseline done — normal)\n- `cron:6f3323ef` still running ✅ (normal 5-min cycling)\n- `cron:53c5832a` completed normally at 23:16 UTC (expected scheduled event)\n- `cron:e7885813` ended (expected — was the 23:14 instance)\n\nNo new failures, no blockers, no pipeline degradation. **Silent — no report.**"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":30965,"output":1036,"totalTokens":46357,"cacheRead":13944,"cacheWrite":412,"cost":{"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1776209417992,"responseId":"062e010b3b7ef026eb124680bbeedf44","__openclaw":{"id":"0fea89bf","seq":5}}]},{"key":"agent:master-orchestrator:cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31","kind":"other","channel":"webchat","origin":{"provider":"heartbea